SIMPLE: renew
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Renew
<hw>Re*new"</hw> <pr>(r?-n?")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Reneved</conjf> <pr>(-n?d")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Renewing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>re-</ets> +
<ets>new</ets>. Cf. <er>Renovate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make
new again; to restore to freshness, perfection, or vigor; to give new
life to; to rejuvenate; to re⟦eum⟧stablish; to recreate; to
rebuild.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In such a night⟦br⟧
Medea gathered the enchanted herbs⟦br⟧
That did <qex>renew</qex> old Aeson.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically, to substitute for (an old obligation
or right) a new one of the same nature; to continue in force; to make
again; <as>as, to <ex>renew</ex> a lease, note, or
patent</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To begin again; to recommence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The last great age . . . <qex>renews</qex> its finished
course.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To repeat; to go over again.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The birds-their notes <qex>renew</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>To make new spiritually; to
regenerate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be ye transformed by the <qex>renewing</qex> of your mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Rom. xii. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Renew</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Renew
<hw>Re*new"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become new, or as new; to
grow or begin again.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Renewability</ent>⟦br⟧
